INSERT INTO `migwatch_species_set` VALUES (1,10,'Bar-headed Goose (Anser indicus)','Larger than domestic duck','','','Easily distinguished from the Greylag goose (A. anser) by a black-banded white head, white line down the neck and yellow beak as opposed to a prominent pink beak in the Greylag.','Widespread winter visitor to the northern plains; locally also in southern India.','','','','','barhgoos_1_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'','Large lakes, rivers and adjoining farmland',NULL,'Bar-Headed-Goose_Sudhir Shivaram copy_1_male.jpg'),(2,11,'Ruddy Shelduck or Brahminy Duck (Tadorna ferruginea)','Larger than domestic duck. ','','','Unmistakable in appearance.','Widespread winter visitor to the plains of north; rare in extreme south.','','lc','','','BrahminyDuck copy_2_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL),(3,2,'Western Marsh Harrier or Eurasian Marsh Harrier (Circus aeruginosus)','Smaller than Black Kite. ','','','Males are predominantly brown, unlike males of other harrier species. Females are chocolate brown with strongly contrasting pale head and throat; and the absence of white on the rump distinguishes Marsh Harrier females from females of other harrier species. The Marsh Harrier has the habit of methodically searching grasslands by flying low over them, looking for prey.','Winter visitor throughout the region.','','lc','','','marsharr_male_3_male.jpg','marsharr_female_3_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Wetlands and grasslands, paddy fields.',NULL,NULL),(5,1,'Northern Shoveler (Anas clypeata)','Smaller than domestic duck. ','Shallow fresh waters like lakes, large irrigation canals, reservoirs, slow rivers.','','The broad shovel-like bill makes this species unmistakeable. Females which look similar to female Mallard\'s (Anas platyrhynchos), but again the Shovelor\'s bill is distinctive.','Common winter visitor throughout the region.','','lc','','','nortshov_male_5_male.jpg','nortshov_female_5_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL),(6,12,'Northern Pintail (Anas acuta)','Smaller than domestic duck.','','','Females are distinguishable from other dabbling ducks by a long neck, slender grey bill and greyish underwing.  Additionally, differs from female Gadwall (Anas  strepera) by absence of white in the wings; from female Mallard (Anas platyrhynchos) in lacking the bright wing-speculum.','Widespread and common winter visitor thought the country.','','lc','','','nortpint_male_br_6_male.jpg','nortpint_female_6_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Freshwater wetlands and brackish lagoons',NULL,NULL),(7,3,'Wood Sandpiper (Tringa glareola)','Similar to that of a quail. ','','','Look for a prominent white supercilium and white spots on the wing and back. In flight, the Wood Sandpiper shows a prominent white underwing, distinguishing it from the similar-looking Green Sandpiper (Tringa ochropus). The call is a good way to distinguish among sandpipers.','','Winter visitor almost throughout the region; plains and low hills.','lc','','','woodsand_7_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Shallow waters with emergent vegetation like marshes, inundated paddy fields, village tanks, etc.',NULL,NULL),(8,19,'Common Sandpiper (Actitis hypoleucos)','About that of a quail','','','Constant bobbing when feeding (other sandpipers may bob, but not constantly) and the prominent white wing-bars in flight are prominent features.','Common and widespread winter visitor to the plains and hills across India.','','lc','','','commsand_8_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Freshwater and coastal wetlands.',NULL,NULL),(9,64,'Green Sandpiper (Tringa ochropus)','Larger than a quail. ','','','Make note of the shorter greenish legs and stockier appearance, darker and less heavily spotted upperparts to distinguish it from the Wood Sandpiper (Tringa glareola).','Widespread during winter; Common in the north, less so in the south.','','lc','','','greesand_9_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Favours small waters such as small rivers, village pools, marshes, rice fields, etc. Usually found near cover; rare in costal habitats',NULL,NULL),(10,68,'Ruff (Philomachus pugnax)','Female (Reeve) is larger than a quail and the male (Ruff) can be much larger (size of a partridge). ','Female (Reeve) is larger than a quail and the male (Ruff) can be much larger (size of a partridge). ','','Bill and leg colour is highly variable in the Ruff. Orange-legged individuals may be confused with the Common Redshank (Tringa totanus) but note different jizz, short bill, scalloped upperparts. The head is distinctly (almost comically) small in relation to the size of the body','Widespread winter visitor or passage migrant; found throughout except parts of northwest, east and Himalaya.','','lc','','','ruff_10_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'','Freshwater lakes, pools and marshes.',NULL,''),(11,61,'Western Black-tailed Godwit or Black-tailed Godwit (Limosa limosa)','Larger than a partridge. ','','','Best distinguished from the Bar-tailed Godwit (Limosa lapponica) in flight, when it shows prominent white wing-bar, single broad black tail-bar and legs trailing well behind tail. Bar-tailed mostly occurs along coastal wetlands, while Black-tailed is predominantly limited to freshwater inland habitats.','','Widespread except in parts of northwest, east and Himalaya.','nt','','','blacgodw_11_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Mainly inland jheels, marshes, lake shallows and muddy shores.',NULL,NULL),(12,53,'Demoiselle Crane (Grus virgo)','Larger than domestic duck.','','','Most similar to the Common Crane (Grus grus) but in the Demoiselle the black of the neck continues down onto elongated breast feathers; this extension of black is observable in flight as well.','Winter visitor and passage migrant. Mostly recorded from northwest India up to central Uttar Pradesh in the east and northern Karnataka in the south. ','','lc','','','democran_12_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Crop fields, river-side sandbanks, reservoirs.',NULL,NULL),(13,39,'Black Stork (Ciconia nigra)','Larger than Grey Heron.','','','Relatively simple to identify. Note red bill and legs and the white of belly that contrast strongly with the glossy black neck, to separate it from others.','Widespread but not too common throughout India; more frequent in the north.','','','','','black stork copy_13_male.jpg',NULL,'juv black stork-1 copy_13_juv.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Along rivers and inland marshy areas.','black stork in flight copy_13_flight.jpg','black stork copy_13_male.jpg'),(14,14,'Osprey (Pandion haliaetus)','About that of a Pariah Kite. ','','','In flight the long narrow wings are held crooked like a gull. Distant hovering bird could also be mistaken for Short-toed eagle (Circaetus gallicus); look for dark carpal patches that the Short-toed eagle lacks.','Widespread winter visitor to the plains.','','lc','','','osprey_14_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Wetlands',NULL,NULL),(15,15,'Common Kestrel (Falco tinnunculus)','About that of a pigeon. ','','','Rufous coloration on upperparts helps separate it from all but the rarer Lesser Kestrel (Falco naumanni). Look for black claws and dark moustachial stripe to tell a Common Kestrel; the Lesser has whitish claws and lacks a dark moustachial stripe.','Widespread winter migrant to the entire country.','','lc','','','commkest_male_15_male.jpg','commkest_female_15_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,'commkest_male_flight_15_behav.jpg','','Open country.',NULL,NULL),(16,23,'Eurasian Wryneck (Jynx torquilla)','Larger than sparrow.','','','Mostly ground dwelling. Easy to identify, but note that some individuals are very pale all over with weak markings. In flight, the long broad tail and shallowly undulating flight pattern are distinctive. It sometimes shows a distinctive behaviour of screwing neck from side to side like a clockwork toy that gives it its name.\r\n','Distributed throughout the dry areas of north and central India in winter; rare in the south.','','lc','','','eurawryn_16_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Open woodlands, scrub forest, semi-desert.',NULL,NULL),(17,6,'Brown Shrike (Lanius cristatus)','About that of a bulbul. ','','','The Rufous Shrike (Lanius phoenicuroides) that is found in parts of western India looks similar but is smaller has a paler and greyer mantle, less buffy underparts and a brighter rufous tail. The Isabelline Shrike (Lanius isabellinus) is also similar-looking but has an obvious white wing patch which the Brown lacks. Juvenile has ‘scalloping’ on the breast. The call is distinctive.','Winter visitor to most of the Subcontinent barring the Himalayas and the western deserts.','','','','','browshri_17_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,'browshri_SamiraAgnihotri_17.mp3',NULL,'','Scrub and open country.',NULL,NULL),(18,30,'Blue Rock-thrush or Blue Rock Thrush (Monticola solitarius)','About that of a Red-vented Bulbul.','','','Males are distinctive. Females lack any strong facial marking, which distinguishes them from the females of other Rock-thrushes.\r\n\r\n','Widespread and common across India in winter.','','lc','','','bluerock_male_18_male.jpg','bluerock_female_18_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Dry rocky areas.',NULL,NULL),(19,28,'Red-throated Flycatcher (Ficedula parva)','Smaller than a sparrow.','','','Ficedula parva and Ficedula albicilla are sometimes treated as separate species. To differentiate between them, note that F. albicilla has a grey breast-band and a much darker tail. The base of the lower mandible is pale yellow in F. parva, while it is completely dark in F. albicilla. The trrrt…trrrt… call of F. parva is frequently interspersed with a sharp electric spark-like tick note, which is absent in F. albicilla\'s vocalization. Female of both these can be confused with the female of the Kashmir (Ficedula subrubra); the Kashmir, however, has more pronounced rufous on the throat and breast','Widespread and common winter visitor to most parts of the country.','','lc','','','Redbreasted Flycatcher_Gopi S copy_19_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Open forest, forest edge, orchards, plantations, gardens.',NULL,NULL),(20,87,'Verditer Flycatcher (Eumyias thalassinus)','About that of a sparrow','','','The pale turquoise coloration is mostly sufficient to identify the males. The females may be confused with the Nilgiri (Eumyias albicaudatus) and should be differentiated by the dull blue (versus brown) wings. The female can also potentially be confused with the male of the Pale Blue (Cyornis unicolor) but lacks the stronger contrast between the light belly and darker upperparts.','Widespread across India except for the dry regions of Rajasthan.','','lc','','','verdflyc_male_20_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Open forests, tall trees in open, cleared forest or forest edges.',NULL,NULL),(21,31,'Bluethroat (Luscinia svecica)','Same size as a sparrow.','','','Relatively easy to identify, note that in winter the breast pattern may be obscured by pale feather tips in male. Females have a prominent submoustachial stripe.','Widespread winter visitor up to Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh in the south; more common in the north.','','','','','bluethroa_male_21_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Scrub or grasslands near water.',NULL,NULL),(22,7,'Black Redstart (Phoenicurus ochruros )','About that of a sparrow. ','','','This species can potentially be confused with the Hodgson\'s Redstart (Phoenicurus hodgsoni) that is found in the Himalayas. The Black, however, lacks any white on the wings while the Hodgson’s has a narrow dull whitish wing-slash. Female Black could also be confused with the female of the Blue-fronted (Phoenicurus frontalis) but for the bold broad black T-patterned tail, which is a distinguishing feature of the Blue-fronted.','Winter migrant across the country, south of the Himalayas.','','lc','','','blacreds_male_22_male.jpg','blacreds_female_22_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Scrub, cultivation.',NULL,NULL),(23,32,'Common Stonechat (Saxicola torquata)','Slightly larger than a sparrow.','','','Very similar to the White-tailed (Saxicola leucura) that is found in parts of Himalayas; note that in the Common the tail is much darker (appears almost black) and  also is shorter.','Locally abundant throughout the region except in the southern peninsula.','','','','','Sib-stonechat_CF male_23_male.jpg','SiberianStoneChat2 copy_23_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Stony scrub, mudflats, sand dunes, grass and reed clumps bordering water.',NULL,NULL),(24,9,'Rosy Starling or Rosy Pastor  (Sturnus roseus)','Smaller than Common Myna.','','','In flight the shape is similar to the Common Starling (Sturnus  vulgaris) but its paler body is diagnostic. The juvenile can also be confused with the Common Starling but note pale lores, rump and stouter yellowish bill. Often moves in groups, and large flocks can be seen in the evenings moving towards roosting sites.','Winter visitor reaching extreme south and at least as far east as West Bengal.','','','','','RosyStarling_SudhirShivram copy_24_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Open country, fallow fields, scrub lands.',NULL,NULL),(25,4,'Barn Swallow or Common Swallow (Hirundo rustica)','About that of a quail. ','','','Look for a dark blue neck, pale, unstreaked belly and a deeply forked tail. Similar species, the Hill Swallow (Hirundo domicola) of the Western Ghats, and the House Swallow (Hirundo tahitica) in the Andaman and Nicobar have relatively greyer bellies and more shallowly forked tails. Can be seen roosting on telegraph wires when they arrive. Often found hawking insects over water bodies.','Winter visitor to the entire Subcontinent including the islands.','','','','','BarnSwallow1_ClementFrancis-id copy_25_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Open country',NULL,NULL),(26,8,'Greenish Warbler or Greenish Leaf-Warbler (Phylloscopus trochiloides)','Smaller than a sparrow','','','Looks a lot like the Large-billed Leaf Warbler (Phylloscopus magnirostris) and is best distinguished from it by the call – a chis-weet for the Greenish (versus a loud dir-tee for the Large-billed). Physically the Large-billed is larger, has a larger and darker bill, mottling on the cheeks and breast, and a more ‘wavy’ eyebrow than the Greenish. Greenish is mostly canopy dwelling; Large-billed is mid-storey.','Winters commonly in the terai belt, wooded parts of Peninsula and common as far east as W Meghalaya.','','','','','Greenish Warbler_26_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Scrub, gardens, forest.',NULL,NULL),(27,77,'White Wagtail (Motacilla alba)','About that of a sparrow ','','','This species shows extremely high subspecies variation; features like the absence of a white supercilium and lack of all-black ear-coverts distinguish it from other Wagtails.','Widespread and common winter visitor across the country.','','','','','White-wagtail_CF_highres copy_27_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Open country, near water',NULL,NULL),(28,5,'Grey Wagtail (Motacilla cinerea)','About that of a sparrow. ','','','The Grey Wagtail has a grey head and grey back; this combination is not seen in any other wagtail species that overwinters in the region. Distinguished from similar-looking young of the Citrine Wagtail (Motacilla citreola), by its yellow vent. The Grey is the only wagtail with a yellow vent.','Winter visitor to the entire region.','','','','','GreyWagtail_ClementFrancis-id2 copy_28_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Near water in wooded areas.',NULL,NULL),(29,35,'Common Rosefinch (Carpodacus erythrinus)','About that of a sparrow','','','Usually the only rosefinch found in the subcontinent south of the Himalayas. In the Himalayas, can be confused with several other species of rosefinches.','Winter visitor to all of northern India and parts of southern India.','','','','','Common Rosefinch Male_29_male.jpg','CommonRosefinch_f_29_female.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Open forest',NULL,NULL),(32,71,'Great Black-headed Gull or Pallas\'s Gull (Larus ichthyaetus)','Larger than domestic duck','Much larger than the other hooded gulls and has a noticeably stronger and more angularly shaped bill. The tri-coloured bill also distinguishes it from other gulls except for the smaller Sooty (Larus hemprichii), which is more sooty-brown than black, grey and white.','','','Winter visitor across the Indian coasts; also found on large rivers in the north.','','','','','GreatblackheadedGull copy_32_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Coast; rarely enters inland lakes and rivers.',NULL,NULL),(34,33,'Blyth\'s Reed-warbler or Blyth\'s Reed Warbler (Acrocephalus dumetorum )','Slightly smaller than a sparrow','','','May be confused with Booted Warbler (Hippolais caligata); head slopes back from the bill in Blyth’s Reed but Booted has rounder head. Call is best identification feature of the Blyth’s: a harsh chuck. May also be confused with other Reed Warblers, all of which either have strong facial markings and/or are much larger.','Widespread and common across the country, except for north-west parts where it is found only as a passage migrant. ','','','','','blyths reed wabler_CF_highres copy_34_male.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Dry habitats and near water, bushes and trees at the edge of forests, orchards.',NULL,NULL);
