p system.  The lava beds at the flat tops(plateaus) are capped by laterite which is usually noticed at an altitude of 900 mts. or more.  The thickness of laterite is approximately 6.30 meters in depth. It is a kind of scoriaceous and variegated clay rock with characteristic red and brown color and is composed essentially of hydrated oxides of alumina and iron.  Rich aluminous varieties of laterite known as ‘bauxite’ occur on plateaus. \r\nThe annual rainfall at the western border of the sanctuary is about 7000 mm. Which decreases to around 3000 mm towards the east. The rainy days in a year are about 107 days on an average. The humidity factor varies from 20 to 50 % in May to 90 to 100 % in the month of July. \r\nThe temperature varies from 12.5o C. in Jan. to 32.2o C in the month of April. The average minimum and maximum temperatures in the sanctuary vary between  19.7 o to 25.3o  C respectively. \r\nThe geological and climatic conditions here have lead to the development of the typical subtropical evergreen and semi-evergreen forests in the western part , while semi-evergreen to moist deciduous types of forests in the eastern parts of the sanctuary.\r\nSite element No.	Name	Location or municipality	Co ordinates of centre point	Area of core\r\nzone (ha.)	Area  of  Buffer\r\nzone (ha.)\r\n1	Radhanagari Sanctuary	Kolhapur	16&#61616; 21&#8242; 00&#8243; N\r\n73&#61616;&#8242;57&#8242; 00&#8243;  E	28232.14	8505.31\r\n\r\nHistory \r\nThe management of the affairs concerned with the forests was done by the forest Department of the former Kolhapur state. It looked after the aforesting, deforesting, issuing hunting licenses and other general administration. Even some Sardars and Jahagirdars had their own forests. In fact the forests were in very good condition in the old days, mainly because of the strict administration of the conservative measures.\r\n 	The area of Radhanagari Wildlife sanctuary was once the hunting reserve of Maharaja of Kolhapur State.  After the merger of Kolhapur State with the Bombay Presidency State in 1948 - 1949, the Forest Division of the state became a part and partial of the Forest Department of the Bombay Govt. In order to meet the  ever growing need of more food, the Govt. undertook schemes to clear the forest areas for agricultural development and extension. But the mismanagement of the schemes lead to little more than just clear felling of the forests. Increasing human encroachment made the natural wealth dwindle and shrink miserably.\r\n	Liberalization of the policy of the Govt. in issuing licenses for weapons to the people for killing the wild animals for protecting crops lead to the heavy toll of the wild animals by way of  poaching  rather than killing them for protecting the crops. Trade of wild life products such as animal skin and flesh made the people go crazy for the easy way of minting money.  \r\n	In 1957 Dajipur Bison Sanctuary was declared as a wild life reserve by Government of Bombay to protect the flora and fauna of the region.  It had an area of 19.2 sq. km. The Govt. was too apathetic even to have a fencing around the reserve.  It was the oldest sanctuaries being declared by the Government of Bombay. 	   \r\nIn Sept 1985, the former Dajipur Bison Sanctuary was extended to an area of  351.16 sq. km. & renamed as Radhanagari Wild-life Sanctuary. The purpose of this extension was to conserve the flora and fauna of the reserve. Also Radhanagari Wildlife Sanctuary is very significant as it is the catchments area of two major hydroelectric & irrigation dam projects.  In conservation proposal in Western Ghats submitted by Wildlife Institute of India Deharadun (Rodger & Panwar) they have proposed the Radhanagari Wildlife Sanctuary to be upgraded as ‘National Park’ with immediate priority.  \r\nThe members of a Kolhapur based organization the GREEN GUARDS have been visiting this area for the last ten years. They have observed and even photographed several wild animals, birds and plants. \r\nBirds \r\n	The Sanctuary region is very rich in Avi-fauna, nearly 250 species of birds are reported in the area.  Interestingly the aquatic avi-fauna is very poor except the egrets, herons, sandpipers and cormorants.  Apparently no ducks or wadders and migratory water birds are found in both the reservoirs.  Out of 77 families enlisted in Indian Birds (Ali and Ripley 1983) 46 families with 156 genera were reported in the region.  The avi-fauna was dominated by members of the family Accipitridae with 30 species (Desai and Samant 1992).  The family includes kites, buzzards, eagles, vultures and harrier.\r\n	Out of the total observed species 179 (60%) species are classified as residents,29 (9.8%) as winter visitors and 56 (19%) winter and summer visitors.  Breeding activity within the sanctuary is recorded in 59 (20%) species of birds which includes birds like Black Eagle, Quails, Pigeons, Vultures , doves, Owls, Pittas, Nightjars, Barbets, Woodpeckers, Larks, Martins, Minivets, Mynas, Crows, Bulbuls , Flycatchers, Warblers, Thrushes and sunbirds, etc.  About 121 (41%) species found in well wooded hilly areas and are confined in the evergreen and moist deciduous biotopes.  \r\n	The Grey Jungle Fowl (Gallus sonneratii) was once very common in the thick  as well as degraded forests of the region.  This is the most commonly hunted species of the region.  Majority of the households are involved in the regular hunting of this bird.  Other birds commonly hunted are Partridges and Quails.  The Pea fowl (Pavo cristatus) was once common in the forests of Radhanagari range in the past now become very rare in the western region.  In the southern region its density is fairly good.  Similar is the case of Malabar Pied Hornbill (Anthracoceros coronatus) which is rarely seen in dense foliage.  The parakeets were common in sanctuary.  Nearly 12 species of family Cuculiformis  are found.  Pied crested cuckoo (Clamator jacobinus) is reported after the monsoon. Brainfever bird Cuculus vanies is very common in this season.\r\nAmong the owls Great horned owl Bubo bubo, Forest eagle owl, Bubo nipalnesis, Dusky horned owl Bubo caromandus, Brown wood owl Strix leptogrammica are sighted at Dajipur, Manbet and Olvan. Many times owls are sighted in sacred groves of Nanivale, Bambarde and Ugwai.\r\nAmong the swifts Alpine Swift Apus melba and Crested tree Swift Hemiprocne longipennis are rare in sanctuary.   Kingfishers, bee eaters, hoopoe, barbets and woodpeckers are common in sanctuary.  Malabar Pied hornbill Anthracoceros coronatus was once common in sanctuary.  While Great pied Hornbill is fairly good in numbers.  All the three species of orioles, Golden oriole Oriolus oriolus, Blacknaped Oriole Oriolus chinensis and Black Headed Oriole Oriolus xanthornus are generally sighted in the forest area.  The mynas, crows and shrikes occurred everywhere.  Minivets, Chloropsis, Yellowbrowed bulbul, Black bulbul are commonly seen near streams and water holes in dense forest.  Flycatchers, warblers, magpie robins, tits, nuthatches, wagtails, flowerpeckers, sunbirds, weaver birds and  munia occur in degraded habitats.  	  \r\nMany birds migrate form Konkan to Western Ghat and vice versa.  Also there are many forest birds which migrate all the way from Himalaya to these areas in winter season.  Many forest birds do breed in these dense forests in rainy season.\r\nWhite bellied sea Eagle has been observed many times perching on the dead stumps in back water of  Radhanagari & Kalammwadi Dams. Its sighting has been confirmed regularly during the months of March to May.  It is regular visitor to the inland reservoirs like Radhanagari Dam, Kalammawadi Dam, Koyana Dam & Chandoli Dam.   Great Pied Hornbill is an uncommon sight in the dense forests of Patacha Dang, Ugawai, Surangi, Kaladang.  Most of these areas are inaccessible.  Osprey has been observed fishing in backwater occasionally.  It is a rare bird here.  Stone Curlew has been often sighted on road at evening near Surangi & Sambar Kond area.  Gray headed bulbul is found in dense foliage in mix party of Black Bulbul & Yellow browed bulbul. Nilgiri Wood Pigeon is a common bird in pigeons  while Pompador Pigeon is a rare bird. Birds of ACCIPITRIDAE (Birds of pray, Vultures) family are found along the Western stiff cliffs of the Sanctuary.  Vultures were found on the western cliff fill 1995, now they are very rate, but still they have been seen in flight near Padgaon area in 2005 & 2006. Black Eagle is the most common birds of pray found in the sanctuary.  Blue winged parakeet is another rare bird found in the sanctuary.  Brown fish owl is found in almost all the big streams in the sanctuary and is a common bird. Ceylon frog mouth bird has been sighted near Hadkyachi Sari area.\r\nThe wildlife in Radhanagari Wildlife Sanctuary has its own importance. It is already subjected to a very harsh exploitation and degeneracy. And it needs an immediate attention for protecting whatever little is left. If this is not done, we might not even know what we have lost, including the precious gene pool.   \r\nThe Sanctuary area has diverse flora and fauna. The area is part of Western Ghats which is one of the “hot spots” of bio diversity. The lush green forest of this area mainly protects the catchment areas of major reservoirs and the bio- diversity in this region makes this sanctuary an important Protected Area. \r\nThe Western Ghats are among the ecologically richest regions of India, next only to the Himalayan in the diversity of biological species.  The biological diversity, which is the variety and variability of plants, animals and micro-organisms; of the Western Ghats is not only important in itself or as the resources base of the diverse human communities who live in he region. It is vital for maintaining the life support system of the peninsular region.  There are about 400 genera of mammals, 275 genera of birds and 60 genera of reptiles in the Western Ghats (Jagtap, 1997).  \r\n      